  "diary": "Monday hit different today. The weather was perfect—sunny, warm—and I could feel the whole city buzzing with that World Cup energy even before I got to the shop. The Light Rail being down made my commute a bit chaotic, but the bus ride gave me time to think. At Vivace, we were slammed during the morning shift. Everyone wanted their coffee before the USA-Wales match kicked off at 11. I trained one of our newer baristas on latte art between rushes, which felt good. Lunch was just a quick sandwich at the counter, but I didn't mind. The afternoon settled into a rhythm—espresso pulls, the hiss of the steam wand, regulars coming in. Got home and spent time with my rooftop garden, watering the tomatoes and herbs. The soil was warm under my fingers. Grabbed some fresh produce at Safeway, cooked a simple pasta with what I'd grown. Then my favorite part: the home brewing session. My kombucha batch is coming along beautifully. Bottled the last batch and settled in with tea and a book. Felt grounded.",
  "thought_process": "Today was about finding rhythm in the familiar. I knew the Light Rail closure would affect my commute, so I left earlier and just accepted the bus crowding. The World Cup buzz was infectious—I could've been annoyed by the early rush, but instead it reminded me why I love shift lead work; there's an energy to feeding people before they gather for something they care about. My mood lifted as the day went on. The morning intensity gave way to afternoon flow, and by evening I was fully in my element—the garden, the kitchen, the fermentation work. That progression from service to creation felt intentional, like I was recalibrating from external demands to internal projects. The weather helped too; sunshine always makes me want to nurture things, whether that's espresso or kombucha or tomato plants.",
